  "text": "Chronic nerve compression leads to fibrosis of the epi-, peri-and endoneurium, endoneurial edema, de-and remyelination and axonal loss. Endoneurial deposits of mucoid substance are frequently encountered. Renaut bodies ( Figure 6C ) are composed of sparse, concentrically arranged, elongated fibroblast-like cells surrounded by ample mucoid extracellular matrix that contains precursors of elastic fibers [CITATION_1] . These structures are usually found in a subperineurial location and are frequent at sites of chronic nerve compression, i.e., in the median nerve within the carpal tunnel. They are often present in the sural nerve and should not be mistaken for organized nerve infarcts.",
